SIMPLE: sexagenary
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sexagenary
<hw>Sex*ag"e*na*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>sexagenarius</ets>, fr. <ets>sexageni</ets> sixty each, akin to
<ets>sexaginta</ets> sixty, <ets>sex</ets> six: cf.
<ets>sexag⟦eacute⟧naire</ets>. See <er>Six</er>.]</ety> <def>Pertaining
to, or designating, the number sixty; poceeding by sixties; sixty years
old.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sexagenary arithmetic</b></col>. <cd>See under
<er>Sexagesimal</er>.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Sexagenary scale</b></col>,
<it>or</it> <col><b>Sexagesimal scale</b></col></mcol>
<fld>(Math.)</fld>, <cd>a scale of numbers in which the modulus is
sixty. It is used in treating the divisions of the circle.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sexagenary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sexagenary
<hw>Sex*ag"e*na*ry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Something
composed of sixty parts or divisions.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A sexagenarian.</def> <rj><au>Sir W.
Scott.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sexagesima</ent>⟦br⟧
